  "answer": "In Cynewulf's Elene (cynewulf-elene-d2d132, ch. 1, paragraph p-7e85bc), Latin shows through the Old English at several registers simultaneously. The most representative cluster is at lines 175-178 of the original:\n\n  'ðæt hie for þam casere cyðan moston godspelles gife, hu se gasta helm, in þrynesse þrymme geweorðad, acenned wearð'\n  ('that they might declare before the Caesar the gift of the gospel, how the soul's helm, glorified in the glory of the Trinity, was born')\n\n1. LOANWORD — 'casere': Directly borrowed from Latin Caesar, used throughout Elene for Constantine (lines 70, 175, 213 etc.). This is not merely a title word: importing Caesar embeds the full theology of Constantinian imperialism — the divinely appointed Roman emperor as God's earthly champion — into Old English verse. The word carries its Roman political and Christian providential weight intact.\n\n2. CALQUE — 'godspel' (in 'godspelles gife', line 175): Cynewulf does not borrow Latin evangelium or Greek euangelion; instead he mints god (good) + spel (tidings/narrative) to translate evangelium semantically. The theological work is double: the word naturalizes the salvific message within a native OE narrative register (spel is the word for heroic story or prophecy), while preserving the semantic core of 'good news.' The Gospel becomes a Germanic spel, accessible to a heroic-poetry audience, yet carrying the full soteriological weight of the Latin tradition.\n\n3. LATIN CONSTRUCTION WITH ENGLISH CLOTHING — 'in þrynesse þrymme geweorðad' (line 178): This phrase ('glorified in the majesty of the Trinity') mirrors the Latin confessional formula in trinitate glorificatus. The in + dative structure imitating Latin in + ablative for expressing state or participation is not the natural OE tendency (which favors genitive constructions). The word þrynesse is itself a calque of Latin trinitas (þrī 'three' + OE abstract suffix -nesse, matching Latin tres + -itas). The whole phrase is OE lexis wearing Latin grammatical clothing, enacting the Trinitarian theology of the creeds — the claim that Christ's incarnation must be understood within the three-personed God.",
